default12.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWorld Vision works according to the 
defaultsocial model of disability
default. Our approach to disability 
defaultinclusion focuses on the social, programming and rights issues
default.
default World Vision seeks to raise awareness of disability to ensure that disabled people’s human rights are respected, to reduce social stigma, break down barriers and to ensure that disabled people
default are included in and not excluded from their community’s development.  World Vision partners with disabled peoples organisations (DPOs) and other organisations to achieve this aim.
default We recognise that not all with disabilities 
defaultwill 
defaultbe categorised as ‘most vu
defaultlnerable’
default.
default 
defaultH
defaultowever World Vision works on the basis that 
defaultonly 
defaultwhen inclusion with equal access to development opportunities is achieved, 
defaultwill 
defaultmost
default individuals
default with disabilities become 
defaultless 
defaultvulnerable.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultWorld Visiondefault’sdefault approach to disability-mainstreamingdefault: defaultour programmes and projectsdefault&#xa0;
default13.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWorld Vision promotes ‘disability mainstreaming’ ensuring that the 
defaultrights 
defaultof disabled people are met
default and as equally represented
default.
default 
defaultDisability is recognised as relevant for World Vision programmes and projects 
defaultacross all sectors
default 
defaulta
defaultnd is deliberately considered at all stages 
defaultthroughout their assessment, design, implementation, monitoring and evaluation. The goal is to enable equal access and opportunities for people with disabilities as programme participants and beneficiaries. 
default&#xa0;
default14.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGiv
defaulten that disabled 
defaultchildren 
defaultare often hidden within population
defaults
default, World Vision proactively seeks to understand the ratio in the population and to ensure that the number of 
defaultindividuals 
defaultwith disabilities participating in World Vision programmes and projects 
defaultwill at least reflect it.
default In World Vision’s long-term area development programmes, we seek to reflect this ratio with the number of CWDs included as sponsored children.
default Although our approach is to include disability issues in all our development programmes
default, we also realise that more targeted (including at 
defaultC
defaultWDs) projects are needed. Inclusive programming alone will not be sufficient to support those who are most vulnerable in the community.
default 
defaultIn this light, we support DFID’s 
default‘twin-track’
default approach to disabilit
defaulty; to promote the deliberate inclusion and 
defaultactive 
defaultparticipation of 
defaultC
defaultWDs in all areas of development whilst not neglecting to also address the particular needs of those individuals.  
