default15.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn 2006 World Vision UK was awarded a 
defaultfive
default year grant from DFID as a part of their Programme Partnership Agreement (PPA). From 2008, the PPA grant amounted to approximately £2.5million per year, part of which was earmarked to mainstream disability into World Vision’s programming. Our strategic obj
defaultective to ‘strengthen the engagement of disabled people in poverty reduction’ 
defaulttook
default a 
defaultlearning 
defaultapproach to mainstream disability across 
defaultparticular 
defaultWV partners. Priority was given to developing training on disability issues for WV staff (by 2011 it had reach
defaulted over 2,500 staff); piloting projects in selected 
defaultDFID priority 
defaultcountries and learning in areas of service delivery such as 
defaultin 
defaulteducation; development of external partnerships with national disabled peoples organisations (DPOs); and evaluation
default. 
defaultWe consid
defaultered a
defaultll of the
defaultse
default elements essential to successfully mainstreaming disability
default. These are
default now central components of our development programming
default.
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default16.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultI
defaultn 2010 World Vision UK produced a training handbook “
defaultTravelling Together – how to include disabled people on
default the main road of development”
default,
default which as well as
default defaulthighlighting the inequality that disabled people face, provides practical tools to promote inclusion in community development.  This handbook 
defaultis 
defaultwidely used
default, 
defaultraising awareness and promoting the inclusion of
default disabled people in development internationally.
default defaultIn designing a disability-inclusive strategy, DFID must take into account that persons with disabilities are diverse and belong to different gender, age, culture, race and ethnicity, socio-economic background, religion, educational background, and family b
defaultackground. 
defaultResearch by 
defaultthe International Institute for Child Rights and Development (
defaultIICRD
default)
default and World Vision on Most Vulnerable Children has
default also 
defaultdemonstrated that CWD who are included in development programmes, supported and cared for by family, peers and
default community and have access to education and social opportunities are far less vulnerable and able to play an active role in their own development
default. Thus we recommend that DFID funds and supports programming solutions that promote the full inclusion of CWD,
default by removing barriers to access to education, health, protection and other vital services.
default 
defaultChildren 
defaultwith disabilities also have different types and degrees of impairment, and these should be taken into account for mainstreaming disability into DFID’s progr
defaultamming.
default&#xa0;
default17.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA major factor that contributed to the positive progress made in mainstreaming disability throughout the
default 2006-2011 PPA programme
default was training World Vision and its partners’ development workers themselves in a
defaultcknowledg
defaulting the
default right
defaults of disabled 
defaultpeople
default to be included in development programmes
default. 
defaultThis allowed our staff to 
defaultthen educate the community and focus on p
defaultrogrammes and projects 
defaultof
default inclusiveness and accessibility, not on individuals’ condition or impairments.
default defaultWorld Vision’s development programming approach deliberately takes a positive, rights-based approach to disability. We focus on the positive ‘assets’ or ‘capabilities’ of individuals, families and communities and seek to build on these, rather than startin
defaultg with a negative deficits approach. 
defaultWe recommend that DFID provides disability equality orientation and refresher training to key stakeholders including
default DFID staff and leadership. This promotes attitudinal and behavioural changes, accessibility and inclus
defaultive programming, in order to eliminate discrimination against persons with disabilities in DFID’s programmes. Wherever possible, disability training should be provided by, or in cooperation with, community-based or national disabled people’s organisations.
