default21.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWorld Vision’s child friendly spaces (CFS) – a child protection
default and 
defaultnon formal 
defaulteducation
default intervention used to support communities in emergencies – allow staff to identify the most vulnerable
default 
defaultchildren
default, including those with disabilities. 
defaultCFS programmes aim to mainstream t
defaulthe needs of disabled children, 
default(
defaultboth as a predetermined condition or as a 
defaultresult of the crisis
default)
default, which provide the necessary provisions for those groups as well as maintaining activities essential to a child’s development such as access to education and healthcare. 
default&#xa0;
default22.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA 3 year research programme by Columbia University is currentl
defaulty assessing the impact of CFS run by World Vision, Save the Children and UNICEF. Its initial findings have found that the effectiveness of child friendly spaces in a camp for Congolese refugees in western Uganda suggest that children who regularly attend C
defaultFS were able to sustain their psychological well-being, where as those who didn’t attend had a marked deterioration. 
defaultAlmost 50% of children categorised as ‘most vulnerable’ who had scored ‘at risk’ levels of psychological difficulties at the time the basel
defaultine was conducted were regular attendees of CFS. All children showed a reduction in difficulties to normative levels at a follow up assessment
default. 
