default23.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe recommend that DFID 
defaultreviews
default 
defaultits humanitarian response strategies to ensure its assistance is reaching the most vulnerable groups, including 
defaultbut 
defaultnot exclusively, those with disabilities. 
defaultWhen working in these challenging contexts, DFID must be prepared to provide both physical and psy
defaultchological rehabilitation to 
defaultall 
defaultvictims
default 
defaultof armed violence. In its recovery programming, DFID must be flexible and consider the potential need to adapt beneficiaries’ livelihoods to better suit their new circumstances.   
default&#xa0;defaultConclusiondefault&#xa0;default24.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn 2000, DFID highlig
defaulthted the critical need to address disability issues in response to tackling poverty. However
default in the years since,
default 
defaultwe have seen discussions around disability-inclusive programming often neglected
default and
default replaced by other DFID priorities. 
defaultWe applaud Lynne Feathe
defaultrstone in driving efforts to return DFID’s attention towards this issue
default however more action is required by DFID to ensure assistance is targeted and inclusive of people, particularly children, with disabilities
default. DFID 
defaultshould
default not view disability as a separate agenda for its development programmes but instead
default,
default commit to achieving inclusion of 
defaultdisabled individuals
default,
default 
defaultthose who are excluded or marginalised in the communities DFID and its partners work in
default.default 
default25.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDFID must demand more fro
defaultm its implementing partners in terms of disaggregating available data by disability, age and gender; 
defaultenabling 
defaultfull transparency 
defaultin measuring 
defaultthe inclusion of disabled individuals 
defaultin the programmes and projects it funds. 
defaultFunding must be made available by DF
defaultID to ensure disaggregation of data can happen effectively.
default26.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn DFID programmes there needs to be a strong
default focus on tackling the discrimination 
defaultexperienced by people with disabilities in communities. Interventions should celebrate an individual’s capabilities, not their impairments 
defaultand promote active participation in the community. The more positive attention paid to how an individual can contribu
defaultte to their own development will aid efforts to breakdown social and physical barriers in society. 
defaultParticular attention should be paid to children with disabilities
default, ensuring they have access to education, healthcare and other basic services that will cont
defaultribute towards the creation of supportive networks for the child. In these instances, they will be less vulnerable to abuse and exploitation often experienced by children with disabilities.
default DFID must recognise that the needs of adults with disabilities and
default the needs of children with disabilities can greatly differ.
default27.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn fragile contexts, DFID must 
defaultmake every effort to reach the most vulnerable children
default. In designing disaster risk reduction strategies, the needs of children with impairments must be considered. In emergency response and medical care must be fully accessible to and inclusive of people with disabilities. The Rights of disabled people and th
defaultat of children must be upheld during and in the aftermath of emergencies, in areas such as refugee and 
defaultinternally displaced persons
default camps.
default28.
default&#xa0; 
defaultGlobally
default, 
defaultthe space to advocate on the inclusion of different development issues in 
defaulta
default post-2015 framework is very cro
defaultwded
default and it will prove challenging to keep the pressure on disability to be included as a cross-cutting theme
default. If DFID is truly committed to bringing disability-inclusion to the forefront of development, it needs to ensure this topic 
defaultremains
default central to the
default development discourse.
default The voices of disabled adults and children should be heard and considered at all levels of decision-making. Opportunities should be opened up to bring representatives of these groups into the centre of the post-2015 development deba
defaultte.
